<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  The consolidated inventory of <strong>Storybook-like tools</strong> that document component libraries
  (<a href="/backlog/624-inventory-the-component-workbench-docs-tool-landscape-storyb/">backlog #624</a>), the
  first stage of the Web Docs feature-pipeline epic
  (<a href="/backlog/623-web-docs-feature-pipeline-inventory-workbench-tools-derive-i/">#623</a>). Until now
  only Storybook + Mintlify had ever been named (as ingest targets in
  <a href="/backlog/426-incumbent-ingestion-adapters-storybook-mintlify-to-the-webca/">#426</a>); this
  enumerates the whole landscape so the feature-surface sweep
  (<a href="/backlog/625-inventory-the-full-feature-surface-across-workbench-tools/">#625</a>) and the
  derive-to-WE-standards decision
  (<a href="/backlog/626-map-workbench-features-to-we-standards-which-intents-blocks-/">#626</a>) have a
  complete, reproducible source list.
</p>
<p>
  The machine-readable registry lives in <code>src/_data/workbenchTools.json</code>; this page renders from
  it. It is <em>complementary</em> to the <a href="/research/benchmark-corpus/">benchmark corpus</a>: that is
  the set of design systems Web Docs would render and benchmark; this is the set of tools that
  <em>document</em> design systems — what Web Docs competes with as a product and ingests from as adapters.
  One is the content, the other the container. Full grounding in
  <code>reports/2026-06-14-component-workbench-landscape.md</code>.
</p>

<h2>Selection criteria</h2>
<p>{{ workbenchTools.inclusionRule }}</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Criterion</th><th>Test</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for c in workbenchTools.selectionCriteria %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ c.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ c.test }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>Category axes</h2>
<p>
  The landscape only makes sense categorized — the tools answer different questions and have different
  business models. The <strong>inventory-format</strong> axis is the load-bearing one for Web Everything: a
  workbench is a renderer over a format, and WE's web-component-native nature makes the
  <strong>Custom Elements Manifest (CEM)</strong> the strongest format to <em>emit</em>.
</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Axis</th><th>What it captures</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for cat in workbenchTools.categories %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ cat.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ cat.axis }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>The landscape</h2>
{% for cat in workbenchTools.categories %}
<h3>{{ cat.label }}</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Vendor</th><th>Model</th><th>License</th><th>Status</th><th>WE role</th><th>Docs</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for s in workbenchTools.sources %}{% if s.category == cat.id %}
    <tr>
      <td><strong>{{ s.name }}</strong></td>
      <td>{{ s.vendor }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.model }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.license }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.status }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.weRoles | join(", ") }}</td>
      <td><a href="{{ s.docsUrl }}">docs</a></td>
    </tr>
    {% endif %}{% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
{% endfor %}

<h2>Two load-bearing priors handed to #626</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>CEM is the format to emit.</strong> Web-component-native declarative JSON (tags, attributes,
    properties, slots, events, CSS parts/vars), already consumed by Storybook-for-web-components, api-viewer,
    and IDEs. <code>api-viewer</code> is the zero-build proof: a single web component that renders CEM as live
    docs + a props playground — the closest existing analog to a WE-native docs element. CSF3 and react-docgen
    are <em>ingest</em> sources, not emit targets.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>The open-core seam is market-validated.</strong> Every commercial tier (Chromatic, Zeroheight,
    Mintlify-hosted) has an OSS or self-hostable counterpart (Lost Pixel, Docusaurus/Starlight, Storybook) —
    exactly the free-OSS-workbench + paid-hosted-conveniences shape
    <a href="/backlog/398-build-the-web-docs-product-fui-open-primitives-plateau-app-o/">#398</a> plans.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>Currency signals</h2>
<p>
  Some tool statuses are themselves findings. <strong>Backlight is retired</strong> (divRIOTS shut it
  1&nbsp;Jun&nbsp;2025) — the fully-hosted browser design-system-IDE model did not endure, a signal for #626
  about where WE should <em>not</em> invest. <strong>React Styleguidist and Pattern Lab are retiring</strong>
  (superseded), but their ideas — docs-from-source and the Atomic Design taxonomy — survive the tools.
  <strong>Histoire</strong> is pre-v1 with effectively one maintainer (a dependency caution). Storybook
  itself remains the anchor: <strong>v9 (Jun 2025)</strong> folded interaction tests, a11y, visual testing,
  and coverage into core.
</p>

<h2>Re-running this sweep</h2>
<p>
  Membership is governed by the selection criteria above so a re-run lands on a comparable list. To refresh:
  re-apply the criteria, add/remove tools, re-check each <code>status</code>/<code>lastChecked</code> and bump
  <code>lastSwept</code> on the file, and record what changed. Retired/retiring tools are deliberately kept —
  their decline is evidence about which models endure. The registry is keyed by stable <code>id</code> so a
  re-run produces a clean diff rather than a rewritten list.
</p>
